  <note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Aelius H. Greek grammarian, 2nd cent. AD, of Alexandria, son of Apollonius
      [11] Dyscolus and his worthy student and successor. ..for a time he lived in Rome and dedicated his main work,
      the Καθολικὴ προσῳδία (Katholikḕ prosōidía) to t the emperor Marcus Aurelius (161-180). He is
      justifiably not seen as a brilliant but as a careful and precise grammarian, the great
      heir and systematician of the Alexandrian tradition of studies on language and of 
      rational analysis of linguistic phenomena.." Montanari, Franco (Pisa), Franke, 
      Thomas (Bochum) and Tinnefeld, Franz (Munich), “Herodianus”, in: Brill’s New Pauly,
      Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert Cancik and , Helmuth Schneider. Consulted online on 30 August 2017</note>
